                          "blocks": {
                            "text_aUVdFR": {
                              "type": "text",
                              "settings": {
                                "text": "<p>Most of the time, kids just need water and a normal diet to stay hydrated. </p><p>Electrolytes become helpful when they’re losing fluids quickly—like during sports, long days in the heat, or when they’re sick with vomiting, diarrhea, or fever.</p><p> In those moments, electrolytes help the body absorb and hold onto water, keeping energy, muscles, and hydration levels steady.</p><p>That said, not all electrolyte sources are created equal. Many sports drinks are packed with excess sugar, artificial dyes, and additives that can do more harm than good—especially for kids who don’t actually need that much. The goal isn’t just adding electrolytes, it’s <strong>replacing what’s lost in a clean, balanced way</strong> without all the extra junk.</p>",
